ratings.comment: Tim is a very nice guy. The lectures are clear but usually boring.  For grading he ranks everyone and only gives out a certain number of As so it's a competitive class.

Tim is the cutest professor and I will miss his class! He is extremely passionate about statistics and he tells us funny stories which keeps us awake in class. Make sure you do the assignments and even if you hand in late, it's better than not handing in at all. Class is curved but quite competitive.

Tim is one of the most genuinely nice professors you will meet at UW. Friendly guy, loves stats, and relates the class well to the real-world. Would definitely recommend taking General Business 304 with him. Overall class is competitive but fairly easy and not too much work.
Really makes sure his students learn. Great guy, good professor

Great prof who really cares about students and takes time to help. Class is curved now. About 20% As, next 30% ABs, and rest of class is Bs with lower grades for really poor performers. I thought the class was very interesting. It is somewhat time consuming as there are many assignments, a large project and 3 exams. But that helps you learn.
Tim is really good, not rude, and ACTUALLY CARES ABOUT STUDENTS.  Something which seems to be few and far between in professors at the UW business school.

Pretty easy class. If you do all of the assignments (which are pretty time consuming), you'll get a good grade. Lectures are pretty boring (for people that are not necessarily interested in stats). Very good professor, though, always willing to help.

Tim is really helpful and willing to help as much as he can during his office hours. Personally, I recommend this class. 8 Assignments and 2 projects in total are not that hard, but TIME-CONSUMING. Quizzes are straight forward, but can be tricky at times. Most people in the class got an AB. Also, Tim doesn't curve his grades an A is fixed at 93
Lectures are straightforward, but kind of boring. He's very helpful though, and tests are pretty easy. Two group projects, both don't require that much work.
